One of my main concerns is understanding if a higher Cost Per Follower (CPF) is acceptable because it attracts high-quality leads, or if it’s simply inefficient. I find it challenging to measure the “quality” of followers since much of it feels like gut instinct rather than data-backed decisions. I’d like a more structured approach to assess follower quality and engagement so that I can avoid wasting ad spend on followers who don’t convert or engage meaningfully. Another issue I face is the length of the sales cycle—it’s inefficient to wait until conversions happen to assess the effectiveness of these ads. I need intermediate metrics that can guide me on when to keep running or pausing an ad. I’ve also been considering lead form ads or DM ads as an alternative, but I’m not sure how to balance capturing qualified leads without significantly increasing costs. I’m interested in exploring lead magnets or low-ticket offers as a way to filter leads, but I’d need guidance on the best structure and process for this. Ultimately, I’m looking for a systematic way to decide which ads to keep running, especially for follower growth, without relying solely on “gut feeling.”

Qualify and convert are almost the same so qualify is knowing if the lead is a good fit based on needs or interest. It's the moment you know if they are worth investing more time in closing converting is turning a qualified lead into an actual sale or closing them.

If you're working exclusively with inbound leads, 100 touchpoints minimum might not work the same since inbound comes with higher intent but maintaining consistent follow-up with the warm leads is very important. For inbound it's about maximizing the conversion vs volume. Focus on engaging the most promising inbound leads 1st. Track response times and prioritize the ones who engage the fastest. Have a functional follow-up system with timelines and how you can re-engage the ones who are interested but haven't booked. Keep the leads warm. It's not bad but it depends on your strategy. Both link in bio and comment in the CTA works but it depends on what your goal is. Link in bio is very direct since people would just click the link and there's no extra steps, you can track the clicks, and keeps the comments clean for real engagement vs spam like "send me the guide" etc. Comments boost visibility. More comments = better reach and you can leverage that thanks to the algorithm. It also adds the personal touch which you can also leverage to build connection. Another is you can keep your YT link in bio which is sick if you're driving traffic. I would combine it so I'd leverage the caption, tease the value (like what you've got) and ask the audience to comment specific things like "DM me". Basically a CTA to get them to your DMs. This way you're hitting the algorithm and giving people options.

So from what I what we have the following components and subcomponents 1) top of funnel ad, which further subdivides into a) targeting b) creative (this further subdivides into: delivery, editing and copy) 2) content on IG a) first impression: thumbnails on feed, bio, logo/icon, highlights b) daily stories c) content: does it actually convert, shift beliefs and relevant to audience? 3) DM/sales a) DM script b) setter/sales calls 1 => quality and quantity of eye balls on profile (proxy for quality of leads) 2 => converting these eyeballs to followers and engagement or "increased lead temperature" (proxy for temperature) 3 => converting temperature to sales (proxy for sales/conversion) Now the question is what is the minimal set of metrics to track in general, and also to disentangle which one of those aspects is off. eye balls from organic is pretty much useless simply because the ad is supposed to give the quality and quantity of leads. To me key metrics for the ad is CPC, CTR, HOOK/HOLD RATES, CPF (cost per follower). Even though here CPF and CPC could also indicate higher quality leads but then together with CTR and H/H rates, it goes more context on how CPC/CPF is to be interpreted? For the mid part follower/clicks ratio and also general temperature in the DMs and sales calls, and maybe show up rate. Is there anything else? For the bottom part closing rate, conversion rates in the DMs. Would love to have your take on which metrics are the most relevant.
